Unfortunately, the iCal widget that [Jeff Croft asked about]({{% wayback "http://jeffcroft.com/blog/archives/2005/05/ical_widget_for.php" %}}) never shipped with Tiger. On the other hand, [Ben Kazez]({{% wayback "http://www.benkazez.com/" %}}) has developed one himself. This one is called [iCal Events]({{% wayback "http://www.benkazez.com/icalevents.php" %}}). It doesn’t yet support all-day calendars, but I’m sure that functionality is on it’s way.

{{<fullimage src="https://cdn.ryanparman.com/img/icalevents-front.gif" alt="Front of widget">}}

{{<fullimage src="https://cdn.ryanparman.com/img/icalevents-back.gif" alt="Back of widget">}}

If you (1) have Tiger, (2) are looking for an iCal Widget, or (3) haven’t already purchased [Konfabulator 2]({{% wayback "http://www.konfabulator.com" %}}) (which includes a state-of-the-art iCal Widget), you should definitely give this one a try. [iCal Events]({{% wayback "http://www.benkazez.com/icalevents.php" %}}).

Thanks so much for the widget, Ben!

**Update:** Ben has asked me to remove my customized version of his widget. If you want to make the changes yourself, you can open the widget package, edit the CSS file, change all references of Helvetica to Verdana, and fiddle with some of the font sizes so that everything fits nicely.

As I was digging through all of the MacWorld keynote coverage this morning, I came across the page for the new [iPod shuffle]({{% wayback "http://www.apple.com/ipodshuffle/" %}}). While I was reading, I saw this:

{{<fullimage src="https://cdn.ryanparman.com/img/ipodshuffle.gif" alt="iPod shuffle: Smaller than a pack of gum and much more fun.[2]">}}

…which was rather clever, I thought. As I got towards the bottom of the page however, I began to laugh out loud much to my co-workers’ bewilderment. This is what I read:

{{<fullimage src="https://cdn.ryanparman.com/img/ipodshuffle_donoteat.png" alt="[2] Do not eat iPod shuffle.">}}

It’s an amazing world we live in, isn’t it?
